✅ 1. Check if SSH keys exist
dir ~/.ssh


If you see id_ed25519 or id_rsa, you already have keys.

✅ 2. Generate an SSH key (Windows)
In Git Bash (recommended):
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "your_email@example.com"


or if not supported:

ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096 -C "your_email@example.com"


Press Enter to accept the default path:

/c/Users/<YourName>/.ssh/id_ed25519

✅ 3. Start SSH Agent
Git Bash:
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"

PowerShell:
Start-Service ssh-agent
Get-Service ssh-agent


(If it shows Running, good.)

✅ 4. Add your SSH key

Git Bash:

ssh-add ~/.ssh/id_ed25519


PowerShell:

ssh-add $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\id_ed25519

✅ 5. Copy the public key

Git Bash:

cat ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub


PowerShell:

Get-Content $env:USERPROFILE\.ssh\id_ed25519.pub


Copy the entire output.

✅ 6. Add the key to GitHub

Go to:

GitHub → Settings → SSH and GPG keys → New SSH Key
Paste your copied key → Save.

✅ 7. Test SSH connection
ssh -T git@github.com


You should see:

Hi <username>! You've successfully authenticated...

✅ 8. Clone using SSH URL
git clone git@github.com:username/repo.git

✅ 9. Convert an existing repo to SSH
git remote set-url origin git@github.com:username/repo.git